h to Development -- tPart Four. Insecurity and Conflicts -- t15 The Impact of Globalization on International Security -- t16 Resource Curse, Globalization, and Conflicts -- t17 The Politics of Oil and Development and Visual Metaphors of the Crisis in Nigeria’s Niger Delta -- t18 Islam and the “Global War on Terror” in West Africa -- tSelected Bibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe first comprehensive work on globalization within the context of sustainable development initiatives in Africa.Few studies of globalization have analyzed its impact on African societies from the viewpoint of sustainable development. This volume answers that need. The essays here contribute to the store of knowledge about globalization in sub-Saharan Africa by documenting the affect of this global force on the continent's growth -- economic, political, and cultural. This interdisciplinary collection provides comprehensive analyses at the international, national, andlocal levels of the theoretical issues revolving around the complex process of globalization, while offering detailed examinations of new models of economic development that can be implemented in sub-Saharan Africa to enhance economic growth, self-sufficiency, and sustainable development. These models are accessible to politicians, public policy analysts, scholars, students, international organizations, nongovernmental actors, and members of the public atlarge. Finally, the essays here provide insightful case studies of African countries that already demonstrate creative, indigenous-based models of entrepreneurship and discuss efforts to achieve sustainable development and economic independence at the grassroots level. Contributors represent the disciplines of law, history, political science, economics, sociology, anthropology, business and management, African studies and art history, criminal justice, and education. Bessie House-Soremekun is the Public Scholar in African American Studies, Civic Engagement, and Entrepreneurship, Professor of Political Science and Professor of Africana Studies at Indiana University-Purdue University, Indianapolis. Toyin Falola is the Jacob and Frances Sanger Mossiker Chair in the Humanities and University Distinguished Teaching Professor at the University of Texas at Austin.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGlobalizationzAfrica. 0aSustainable developmentzAfrica. 4aAfrican Studies. 4aModern History. 4aPolitics & Economics. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Development / Sustainable Development.2bisacsh  aAfrica.  aAfrican American studies.  aAfrican studies.  aanthropology.  aculture.  adevelopment.  aeconomics.  aglobalizzation.  apolitics.  apostcolonialism.  asociety.  asustainablity.1 aAdesanya, Aderonke Adesola, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAgbor-Baiyee, Baiyee-Mbi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAjayi, Iyiola Alade, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBabalola, Adeyemi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBessie House-Soremekun, Bessie, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBravo, Karen E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClark, Gracia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Sousa, Ricardo Real Pedrosa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFalola, Toyin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFalola, Toyin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHouse-Soremekun, Bessie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKpinpuo, Stephe